BofA on $AVGO:

TPU may match GB300 but likely not Vera Rubin.

As shown in Exhibit 1, TPUv7 is more power-efficient than NVIDIAâ€™s GB300 for workloads it is optimized for, such as pre-training and FP8 LLM training (5.42 TFLOPs/W for TPU vs. 3.57 TFLOPs/W for GB300). TCO can be up to ~40% lower for FP8, though up to ~45% higher for FP4/NVFP4.

While this highlights TPU competitiveness, real-world performance may vary significantly due to workload type, ecosystem/model support, and software optimization.

Moreover, NVIDIAâ€™s Vera Rubin (2H26) with HBM4, new Kyber racks, and architectural upgrades could deliver major TCO advantages over TPUv8 (2027), which is likely only a minor upgrade (HBM3e, 2x lower memory bandwidth).

Risks: Google selling TPUs directly, MediaTek

If Google sells TPUs as merchant silicon (beyond GCP rental), it would create direct competition for AVGOâ€™s custom ASIC customers (Meta, ByteDance, OpenAI). Google could also add MediaTek as a design partner for TPUv8 (high-end TPUv8AX to AVGO, low-end TPUv8X to MediaTek), reducing AVGO share risk.

profile_bio.description: Fund partner & Professor (CFA), 30 yrs in macro & tech. Longform threads on AI, semis, cycles. Buy-side mindset, independent research. ä¸­æ–‡çŸ­è¯„äº’åŠ¨æ‹†é€»è¾‘.

quoted_tweet.text:
People see someone hot in well fitted denim and want the same jeans. That is not ideology. That is pricing. 

Tonight $AEO is up 10% after hours on an earnings beat. The stock is just catching up to what human nature priced months ago.

Investing works the same way.

You do not need Wall Street models, you need common sense and a feel for mood shifts.

Four months ago when I flagged AEO off that â€œproblematicâ€ ad, people were still laughing.

â€œIt is just a jeans commercial, why drag politics and Nazis into it.â€
Moral noise on top of very old instincts.

From July 29 to now the stock did what cultural hinge names tend to do: it moved cleanly, roughly eighty five percent up before tonight, then another jump after earnings. No prophecy. Just reading behavior and sentiment on different clocks.

The hinge was never complicated.
On the ground, the US consumer was not nearly as dead as the recession narrative wanted you to believe. People kept walking into malls, tapping cards, buying clothes. The macro story was depressed. The actual basket was not.

At the same time, taste was clearly turning. Post woke fatigue was real. Health, sex appeal, beauty were quietly allowed back on screen. Good ads are not political essays. They are calibrated ways of putting desire back into the frame.

Q3 just stamped the thesis in numbers: revenue up 6 percent, comps up 4 percent versus 2.7 expected, EPS 0.53 vs 0.44, full year guide raised and the stock popped another 10 percent after hours.

AEO sits exactly at that intersection. First the ad detonated attention. Then earnings expectations started to move up. Then the multiple crawled from sub 10 back toward something like a normal range.

If they deliver 1.5 dollars EPS next year and you put a very ordinary 15 times on it, you are in a 20 to 30 dollar band. The â€œstoryâ€ ends and grade school arithmetic takes over.

Meanwhile a whole ecosystem of commentators rushed to hang â€œeugenicsâ€ on a pair of jeans. Reality stayed simple: you see someone who looks good in a fit, you want the same fit, you want to look better. That is not a political project. It is a species trait.

The same rule applies to markets.
You do not need to reverse engineer every Wall Street spreadsheet. You need to notice when culture turns, when fear has crushed perfectly normal demand, and when a brand is sitting right on the fault line of that reversal. Those are the hinge moments.

The 85% move in AEO, plus a blowout quarter and an after hours spike, was not genius. It was just refusing to let narrative drown out observable behavior. 

Some people stay glued to headlines. Others bother to look up and ask a boring question: what are ordinary people actually buying, wearing, wanting right now.

tweets.text:
Intel up ~9% today on a simple headline: 14A, the post-18A node, is getting positive feedback from two potential foundry customers and is already in co-design with them.

The street will read this as â€œanother process node storyâ€. Thatâ€™s the wrong frame.

18A is about whether Intel can re-enter physics reality and ship a credible advanced node.

14A is about whether customers are willing to underwrite a ten-year foundry relationship on top of that:
2nd gen GAA, PowerDirect back-side power, High-NA EUV with 15â€“20% perf/watt and 30% density gains vs 18A on paper.

If 18A works, the market stops laughing.

If 14A lands anchor customers, the market loses the option to treat Intel as a temporary bounce. It becomes a structural second pole in the compute stack.

My base case Intel thesis never assumed 14A execution.

It was built on: Apple using 18A as a hedge on Taiwan. Google/Meta evaluating Intel packaging as a second lifeline. US policy needing a domestic anchor to avoid single-point failure.

14A is pure optionality on top of that.

The more customers are willing to co-design this far out, the more the equity stops being a value trap and starts behaving like a long-duration geopolitical asset.
